panies. The emergent middle classes, the creation of a public sphere, and nationalist politics transformed the medical culture of modern India and generated conflict between Western and Indigenous medical systems and their practitioners. Nandini Bhattacharya demonstrates that these disparate therapies were sustained through the tropes of purity or adulteration, potency or lack of it, and epistemic heritage, even when their material configuration often differed little.Uniquely engaging with the cultures of both consumption and production in the country, Disparate Remedies follows the evolution of medicine in colonial India as it confronted Indian modernity and changing public attitudes surrounding health and drugs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGeneric drugszIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aGeneric drugszIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPharmaceutical industryzIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPharmaceutical industryzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPharmacopoeiaszIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPharmacopoeiaszIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / South / India.2bisacsh  aAlembic.  aAyurveda.  aBDAmin.  aBaroda.  aBengal.  aBritish.  aBurroughs Wellcome.  aChemicals.  aGovernment.  aKala Bhavan.  aMedical.  aMysore.  aNehruvian.  aPCRay.  aPharmacopeia.  aRNChopra.  aStore.  aUnani.  aactive.  aalcohol.  acinchona.  acolonial.  adigitalis.  adrugs.  aefficacy.  aexcise.  aimport.  aindustrial.  aindustrialization.  aingredients.  amodernity.  apharmacy.  aprincely.  ascience.  astate.  asubstitution.  atrade.  atropical.  aurban.  awestern.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto P